# arch-distros — survey of the arch linux family
#
# "arch-based" is a family, not a single distro. what they share:
#
#   - pacman as the package manager (see [[pacman]])
#   - the AUR as the community build-recipe repo (see [[pacman]] AUR section)
#   - .pkg.tar.zst binary package format
#   - rolling release (with one big exception — SteamOS does point releases)
#   - the arch wiki as de-facto canonical documentation
#
# what they DON'T share:
#
#   - installer (arch ships archinstall; most derivatives ship calamares)
#   - init system (artix offers openrc/runit/s6/dinit; everyone else is systemd)
#   - default desktop, kernel, default filesystem, theming, repo policy,
#     how aggressively they patch packages, how AUR-friendly they are.
#
# this file is a tour, not a benchmark. picking one is mostly about how much
# setup you want to do yourself and how close to upstream you want to live.


WHERE EACH ONE SITS — ONE-LINE PITCHES
--------------------------------------

# Arch Linux       — the upstream. minimal base, you assemble the rest.
# Manjaro          — arch with a 2-week safety buffer + calamares installer.
# EndeavourOS      — thin friendly layer over pure arch, vanilla repos.
# Garuda           — performance/gaming-focused, btrfs+snapper out of box.
# CachyOS          — performance-tuned packages (x86-64-v3/v4), BORE sched.
# Artix            — arch without systemd (openrc / runit / s6 / dinit).
# SteamOS 3        — valve's immutable arch for the Steam Deck.
# RebornOS         — calamares-driven, lots of DEs to pick at install.
# ArcoLinux        — educational ladder from "easy" to "build it yourself".
# BlendOS          — immutable, container-based ("distroless arch").


ARCH LINUX — the upstream
-------------------------

# what it is: minimal rolling-release distro. you get a base system and the
# pacman repos; everything else is a deliberate choice. the install is a
# scripted but explicit walk: partition, mkfs, pacstrap, fstab, chroot,
# bootloader, network, user. no GUI installer historically (archinstall is
# the official scripted helper now, but the wiki install is still the
# expected default knowledge).

# release model: TRUE rolling. packages land on stable as soon as the
# maintainer pushes them. no "branches" — there's just current.

# installer: archinstall (TUI, optional). vanilla install is wiki-driven.
sudo archinstall                       # menu-driven, profiles supported

# package count: ~14k in core/extra (formerly core/extra/community — those
# were merged in 2023). AUR adds ~90k user recipes on top.

# kernel: linux (vanilla, latest stable). also packaged: linux-lts,
# linux-zen, linux-hardened. switch with `pacman -S linux-lts` + regenerate
# initramfs + update bootloader (see [[grub]]).

# target audience: people who want to know exactly what's installed and
# why, and who treat "read the wiki" as a feature.

# strengths:
#   - smallest attack surface by default
#   - newest userspace anywhere short of Tumbleweed
#   - the arch wiki is the best linux documentation in existence
#   - AUR access is first-class
# trade-offs:
#   - you OWN the install. no calamares fallback if something breaks.
#   - rolling-release maintenance is a permanent low-grade chore. read
#     archlinux.org/news before any -Syu that's been >2 weeks since the
#     last one — manual-intervention notices live there.


MANJARO — staged-rolling, mainstream
------------------------------------

# what it is: arch with a 2-week soak buffer. packages flow unstable →
# testing → stable. you're on stable by default and running roughly two
# weeks behind pure arch in batched dumps.

# release model: STAGED ROLLING. three branches (stable, testing,
# unstable). you can change with pacman-mirrors (see [[pacman]] MANJARO
# SPECIFICS). branch downgrades are not really supported.

# installer: calamares. KDE, GNOME, XFCE are the official flagship spins;
# community spins cover most other DEs. partitioning offers btrfs with the
# @ / @home / @cache / @log subvolume layout (see [[btrfs]] MANJARO +
# TIMESHIFT INTEGRATION).

# package management: pacman + pamac front-end (GUI and CLI). pamac talks
# to manjaro's repos AND optionally the AUR (off by default — toggle
# EnableAUR in /etc/pamac.conf).

# the "manjaro repos" matter: manjaro does NOT use arch's repos directly.
# this is why AUR breakage can hit manjaro stable harder than pure arch —
# an AUR PKGBUILD targets current arch, which may be a glibc bump ahead of
# manjaro stable.

# kernel: manjaro ships mhwd-kernel, a side-by-side kernel manager. install
# multiple kernels, boot whichever:
mhwd-kernel -li                        # list installed
mhwd-kernel -l                         # list available
sudo mhwd-kernel -i linux612

# target audience: newcomers to arch who want a working desktop in 20
# minutes and don't want to assemble it themselves. people running
# bleeding-edge for daily work but with a small breakage buffer.

# strengths:
#   - calamares + sane defaults + flagship DEs
#   - hardware detection (mhwd) handles proprietary nvidia drivers cleanly
#   - 2-week buffer catches some upstream regressions
#   - btrfs + timeshift-autosnap snapshots before every -Syu
# trade-offs:
#   - manjaro's own repos add a second layer of "could be the bug"
#   - AUR + staged-rolling friction (glibc-skew etc, see [[pacman]])
#   - manjaro has had cert/keyring/SSL incidents in the past — the
#     team has a reputation for occasional sloppy ops. for production
#     servers this is a reason to pick pure arch instead.
#   - DDOSing aur.archlinux.org accidentally (twice, 2020-2021) — fixed,
#     but reputational damage stuck.


ENDEAVOUROS — the EndeavourOS sweet spot
----------------------------------------

# what it is: spiritual successor to antergos (which folded in 2019). a
# thin friendly layer over PURE arch — endeavour adds a calamares installer
# and a welcome app, then gets out of the way. you end up on arch's actual
# repos, not a forked copy.

# release model: TRUE rolling (because the repos are arch's, with one tiny
# endeavour-specific repo for the welcome app and themes).

# installer: calamares. online install lets you pick the DE; offline
# install is XFCE only. supports btrfs / luks / lvm / encryption out of
# box. nvidia non-free option in the installer.

# package management: pacman straight; yay is preinstalled for AUR.

# target audience: people who want "arch but I didn't want to hand-write
# fstab today". the most-recommended derivative on r/archlinux these days.

# strengths:
#   - effectively pure arch — `cat /etc/pacman.conf` proves it
#   - very small endeavour-only footprint (welcome app, themes)
#   - active and friendly community forum + wiki
#   - calamares installer with all the bits people forget (microcode,
#     timeshift, nvidia drivers, swap-with-hibernate)
# trade-offs:
#   - you still own the rolling-release maintenance burden (read
#     archlinux.org/news before big -Syu)
#   - no auto-snapshots out of the box (you opt into timeshift)
#   - no staged-rolling buffer — endeavour IS pure arch's timeline


GARUDA — gaming/performance focused, opinionated
------------------------------------------------

# what it is: arch + zen kernel + btrfs+snapper + chaotic-aur + a heavily
# themed KDE (the "Dragonized" edition). targets gamers and people who want
# everything plugged in by default.

# release model: rolling. uses arch repos + chaotic-aur (a binary mirror of
# popular AUR packages, prebuilt). chaotic-aur means less makepkg waiting
# for popular AUR stuff.

# installer: calamares. btrfs is the strongly-pushed default and the
# snapshot tooling assumes it.

# kernel: linux-zen by default. zen is a vanilla kernel with desktop-
# responsiveness patches (BFQ scheduler, MuQSS-style tweaks, lower default
# latencies). small wins for interactivity, occasional regressions for
# servers — don't run garuda on a server.

# package management: pacman + pamac + chaotic-aur. snap is intentionally
# absent (see [[snap]] for the Canonical politics).

# notable extras out of the box:
#   - btrfs with auto-snapshots via snapper + grub-btrfs (see [[btrfs]])
#   - garuda-gamer meta-package (steam, lutris, gamemode, mangohud,
#     proton-ge, wine-staging, etc.)
#   - garuda-assistant: GUI maintenance frontend
#   - garuda-boot-options: GUI for kernel args
#   - fish as the default shell (with bash-style fallbacks)

# target audience: gamers, performance-curious users, people who want a
# loaded desktop on day one and don't mind heavy theming.

# strengths:
#   - "I want to game on linux" → fewer config hours than anywhere else
#   - snapper + grub-btrfs are pre-wired (rare in the arch family)
#   - chaotic-aur means popular AUR pkgs are prebuilt
# trade-offs:
#   - heavy. dragonized KDE is ~3GB of theming. minimal editions exist.
#   - opinionated defaults — fish, zen, btrfs — fight you if you don't want them
#   - chaotic-aur adds a third-party binary repo to your trust surface


CACHYOS — performance-tuned, x86-64-v3/v4
-----------------------------------------

# what it is: arch derivative with custom-compiled packages targeting
# modern CPU baselines (x86-64-v3 and v4), the BORE / sched-ext schedulers,
# and a curated set of performance defaults.

# release model: rolling. uses cachyos's own binary repos (the perf-
# rebuilt packages) layered over arch's.

# the v3/v4 angle: x86-64-v3 = haswell+ (2013+, AVX2, BMI2, FMA);
# x86-64-v4 = AVX-512 (icelake-server, sapphire rapids, zen 4+). cachy's
# installer detects your CPU and configures /etc/pacman.conf to pull from
# the highest tier your hardware supports. real-world wins are
# benchmark-noisy but consistent at the 1-5% level on compute-heavy code
# (compilers, ffmpeg, blender). gaming wins mostly come from the
# scheduler, not the binaries.

# kernel: cachyos-cachy (sched-ext + BORE + assorted patches) by default;
# linux-cachyos, linux-cachyos-lts, linux-cachyos-rt are also packaged.
# multiple kernel managers (cachyos-kernel-manager) for switching.

# installer: calamares. asks about FS (btrfs default), DE, kernel,
# scheduler, shell. unusually opinionated installer for an arch derivative.

# target audience: enthusiasts who care about benchmarks, gamers chasing
# 1% lows, anyone with a recent CPU who wants the binaries that match it.

# strengths:
#   - measurable perf wins for the rare benchmark that's CPU-bound
#   - bleeding-edge scheduler experimentation, often before mainline
#   - active 2024-2026 momentum, gaining mind-share
# trade-offs:
#   - cachy's repos are another trust surface
#   - sched-ext is still maturing; "perf-tuned" sometimes means
#     "unstable for my workload"
#   - newer project — smaller community than manjaro/endeavour


ARTIX — arch without systemd
----------------------------

# what it is: arch with the systemd dependency stripped out. ships your
# choice of init system at install time: OpenRC, runit, s6, or dinit.

# release model: rolling. artix has its own repos (forks of arch's pkgs
# with systemd deps stripped). you can additionally enable arch's repos
# but it's not on by default and creates breakage potential.

# installer: a TUI (artix-installer) + a calamares spin. less polished
# than manjaro/endeavour but functional.

# package management: pacman, plus init-system-specific service-mgmt:
sudo rc-service nginx start            # OpenRC
sudo sv up nginx                       # runit
s6-rc -u change nginx                  # s6
dinitctl start nginx                   # dinit

# target audience: people who actively object to systemd (anti-monoculture
# philosophy, prefer simpler init scripts, embedded use cases). small
# group but vocal.

# strengths:
#   - the only mainstream rolling-release option without systemd
#   - four init systems to choose from at install
# trade-offs:
#   - significant package compatibility friction — a chunk of the arch
#     ecosystem assumes systemd (timers, journald, logind, networkd, .service)
#   - smaller community, slower bug-fix turnaround
#   - "we don't like systemd" is occasionally an ideological stance more
#     than a technical one. be honest with yourself about why.


STEAMOS 3 — valve's immutable arch for Steam Deck
-------------------------------------------------

# what it is: arch-based, immutable (read-only root), A/B partition scheme,
# KDE Plasma in desktop mode + a gamescope/steam-overlay session in gaming
# mode. ships on the Steam Deck and ROG Ally X.

# release model: POINT RELEASES, not rolling. valve curates updates and
# pushes them as system images. the A/B scheme means a failed update
# rolls back automatically.

# package management: pacman is present but blocked on the immutable
# root. flatpak is the supported way to install applications. there's an
# escape hatch (`steamos-readonly disable`) but anything you install that
# way gets blown away by the next system update.

# what it tells you about arch: immutable arch is possible, and works.
# valve effectively productionized the model that BlendOS / Vanilla OS
# / Fedora Silverblue have been exploring.

# target audience: Steam Deck owners. "general purpose desktop SteamOS"
# is not really a goal — the desktop mode is functional but designed as
# an escape hatch from gaming mode, not a daily driver.

# strengths:
#   - "it just works" for the target hardware
#   - A/B + immutable = unbrickable under normal use
#   - gamescope is genuinely excellent
# trade-offs:
#   - pacman is mostly read-only — flatpak everything
#   - not really a desktop distro despite the KDE session


HONORABLE MENTIONS
------------------

# RebornOS         — calamares installer with ~15 DE options at install
#                    time. arch repos directly + a small reborn repo.
#                    quieter than endeavour but similar in spirit.
#
# ArcoLinux        — a teaching project. ships in three tiers: ArcoLinuxL
#                    (full), ArcoLinuxD (do-it-yourself with helper scripts),
#                    ArcoLinuxB (build your own). the founder's youtube
#                    series is part of the value prop.
#
# BlendOS          — immutable, container-based. "distroless" arch — apps
#                    run in containers, base is read-only, atomic updates.
#                    interesting experiment, niche audience. compare with
#                    fedora silverblue / vanillaOS.
#
# Anarchy / RebornOS / ArchBang / Archcraft / Mabox — long tail of
# "arch + pretty defaults" remixes. mostly pick-by-screenshot; the
# underlying system is the same arch.


HOW TO PICK — a practical decision tree
---------------------------------------

# "I want to learn how linux is glued together":
#     → Arch Linux. do the wiki install at least once. it's a rite of
#       passage but also a genuine learning experience.
#
# "I want pure arch but don't want to hand-write fstab":
#     → EndeavourOS. closest you can get to vanilla arch with a GUI installer.
#
# "I want bleeding-edge but with a small safety buffer":
#     → Manjaro. accept the 2-week staged-rolling trade-off and the AUR
#       skew issues. read forum stable-update threads before -Syu.
#
# "I want to game and I don't want to configure proton/lutris/mangohud":
#     → Garuda (gaming edition) or CachyOS. garuda is more loaded;
#       cachy is more performance-tuned.
#
# "I have a modern CPU and benchmarks matter to me":
#     → CachyOS. v3/v4 binaries are real, sched-ext is interesting.
#
# "I don't want systemd":
#     → Artix. pick an init system at install. expect ecosystem friction.
#
# "I bought a Steam Deck":
#     → SteamOS 3. don't replace it unless you have a specific reason.
#
# "I'm running a server":
#     → Arch Linux, NOT a derivative. the derivatives are all
#       desktop-oriented. for servers, also seriously consider Debian
#       stable or Rocky/Alma — rolling release on a server you can't
#       reach physically is a stressful life choice.


COMMON MISCONCEPTIONS
---------------------

# 1. "manjaro is just arch with a delay" — not quite. manjaro maintains
#    its own repo with its own packaging decisions. it's arch-flavored,
#    not arch-with-a-buffer.
#
# 2. "endeavour is arch with a different name" — closer but still wrong.
#    endeavour has its own (small) repo for the welcome app and themes.
#    the bulk of your packages do come from arch's actual repos.
#
# 3. "the AUR is part of arch" — no, it's user-submitted build recipes
#    hosted by the arch project but unreviewed and unsupported. helpers
#    like yay/paru drive it. every derivative inherits AUR access, but
#    AUR breakage is on you, not on the derivative.
#
# 4. "rolling release = always broken" — managed rolling (manjaro stable,
#    endeavour with discipline) is fine for desktops. unmanaged ("I'll
#    -Syu when I feel like it") is where the pain comes from. read
#    [[pacman]] MANJARO SPECIFICS for the maintenance loop.
#
# 5. "arch is for elitists" — outdated meme. the wiki is gold, the
#    package surface is huge, and archinstall makes a working system
#    in ten minutes. the difficulty is maintenance discipline, not
#    install ceremony.
#
# 6. "X is faster than Y because benchmarks" — most arch-family perf
#    differences are scheduler/kernel choice and userland defaults,
#    not binary tuning. installing linux-zen on vanilla arch gets you
#    most of what garuda's perf reputation is built on.


COMPARING WITH OTHER FAMILIES
-----------------------------

# debian family (see [[apt]], [[deb]]):
#   - point release, conservative, big package count, slow.
#   - LTS-friendly, server-friendly. ubuntu adds snaps (see [[snap]]).
#
# fedora / RHEL family (see [[dnf]], [[rpm]]):
#   - 6-month cadence, modern userspace, copr for community packages.
#   - silverblue for the immutable model.
#
# openSUSE family (see [[zypper]], [[btrfs]]):
#   - Tumbleweed = QA'd rolling (the closest non-arch rolling release).
#   - root-on-btrfs + auto-snapper is the gold-standard reference setup.
#   - usually the next-best rolling-release answer if arch doesn't fit.
#
# alpine (see [[apk]]):
#   - musl + busybox + openrc, tiny base. container/embedded focus, not
#     a desktop distro.


